-- Central African Community Growth May Slow to 5.7% This Year
-- B y   P i u s   L u k o n g
-- 2012-03-29T06:57:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-03-29/central-african-community-growth-may-slow-to-5-7-this-year.html
The  Central African Economic and
Monetary Community  trimmed its growth forecast for 2012 to 5.7
percent from 6 percent, Bank of Central African States Governor
Lucas Abaga Nchama said.  Inflation in six-nation community is expected to accelerate
to 2.8 percent from 2.2 percent, Nchama told reporters yesterday
in the Cameroonian capital, Yaounde, after the bank’s Monetary
Policy Committee held its first meeting of the year.  Cemac, as the community is known, groups Cameroon,  Central
African Republic , Chad, Congo Republic,  Equatorial Guinea  and
Gabon.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Pius Lukong in Yaounde via Accra at 
 ebowers1@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Antony Sguazzin at 
 asguazzin@bloomberg.net . 